         <div type="translation">
            <p><choice corresp="#a1"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:hackstein1995"/><citedRange>54</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:adams2012"/><citedRange>12</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">(he rose), [and] hungry and thirsty he saw these artisans standing nearby, and crushing those very four, all together, with his paw he killed them</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a1 #a2"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1997"/><citedRange>103</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1997"/><citedRange>88</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a1 #a2 #a3 #a4 #a5 #a6 #b1 #b2 #b3 #b4 #b5 #b6"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:sieg1944"/><citedRange>16</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a2"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1966"/><citedRange>264</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1976a"/><citedRange>78</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1979a"/><citedRange>259</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">and ate them all up. || In the Y.-tune: || Their craftsmanship was good; from the broken bones they let grow the lion,</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a2 #a3"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:hackstein1995"/><citedRange>137</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">Gut war ihre Kunstfertigkeit. Aus den zerbrochenen Knochen ließen sie den Löwen erwachsen/stellten sie sich einen Löwen her, [aber] an die Möglichkeit, dass sie von dem Löwen gefressen werden könnten [wtl. das Gefressenwerdenkönnen] hatten sie nicht gedacht, [und so] wurden sie Nahrung ihres Löwen durch [ihre] Dummheit.</seg><seg type="sec_transl" resp="TI">Good was their artistry.  From the broken bones the lion they let grow forth, [but] the possibility of being eaten by the lion they had not considered, [and thus] they became the food of their lion because of [their] foolishness.</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt1974"/><citedRange>180, 440</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a2 #a3 #a4 #a5"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1957"/><citedRange>159</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a3"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1952"/><citedRange>57</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1954"/><citedRange>758</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[But] the lion’s eating/hunger they had not considered, [and] they became food for their lion because of their ignorance. The broken bones</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a3 #a4"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt1974"/><citedRange>83, 304f, 401, 495</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a3 #a4 #a5"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt1974"/><citedRange>127, 388</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">Sie sammelten die zerbrochenen Knochen des Löwen und stellten ihn mit Kunstfertigkeit [wieder] her. / Die zerbrochenen Knochen des Löwen haben [hatten?] sie gesammelt, mit Kunstfertigkeit hatten sie ihn [wieder]hergestellt, [aber] die eigenen Knochen brachten sie (an die Stelle) der Löwenknochen [und] gingen zugrunde.</seg><seg type="sec_transl" resp="TI">They gathered the lion's broken bones and with skill restored it [i.e. the lion]. / The broken bones of the lion they [had?] collected, with artistry they had restored it, but the[ir] own bones they brought (in the place) of the lion's bones [and] perished.</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt1974"/><citedRange>83, 127, 304-5, 388, 495</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">of the lion they had gathered, with craftsmanship they had restored him, [but their] own bones they brought (in place of) the lion’s bones</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a5"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:carling2000"/><citedRange>85</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1958a"/><citedRange>151</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[and] they perished. 1. Therefore wisdom is the very best in the world; [only] the one who has knowledge, he is of human birth.</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a6"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">Puṇyavān [“the Virtuous”] speaks: Whatever you each have said for yourselves to see as a praise of beauty, energy, skill (and wisdom),</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a6 #b1"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1957"/><citedRange>221</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1958a"/><citedRange>152</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">in my opinion virtue alone is the very best of all here. For: || In the N.-tune: ||</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b2"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:carling2000"/><citedRange>242</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1952"/><citedRange>54</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1954"/><citedRange>748</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">beauty and a hero’s strength are to be regarded as the fruit of virtues; if one is born into a noble incarnation, if one becomes a rich Koṭīśvara [“Lord over 10 000 000”],</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b3"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:carling2000"/><citedRange>86</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1957"/><citedRange>99</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">a good reputation comes, virtues being the way to universal domination and the divine world.</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b3 #b4"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1957"/><citedRange>259</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b3 #b4 #b5"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1957"/><citedRange>161</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">The coming together with the good ones [and] the reaching of the Nirvāṇa, virtue facilitates [this] without labour. 1. By virtue</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b5"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:carling2000"/><citedRange>138</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">empowered the world-ruling king with [his] entourage walks to the airspace; the people on the four continents, as a fruit of virtue, submit to him.</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b5 #b6"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:hackstein1995"/><citedRange>68</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b6"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:carling2000"/><citedRange>240</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:hackstein1995"/><citedRange>99</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1972"/><citedRange>431</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1983"/><citedRange>35</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">A person that has practiced virtue, does not come into misery, does not come into hardship. With the army of virtue all enemies</seg></seg></choice></p>
