               <item n="m_translation_old">a1 (he rose), [and] hungry and thirsty he saw these artisans standing nearby, and crushing those very four, all together, with his paw he killed them
a2 and ate them all up. || In the Y.-tune: || Their craftsmanship was good; from the broken bones they let grow the lion,
a3 [But] the lion’s eating/hunger they had not considered, [and] they became food for their lion because of their ignorance. The broken bones
a4 of the lion they had gathered, with craftsmanship they had restored him, [but their] own bones they brought (in place of) the lion’s bones
a5 [and] they perished. 1. Therefore wisdom is the very best in the world; [only] the one who has knowledge, he is of human birth.
a6 Puṇyavān [“the Virtuous”] speaks: Whatever you each have said for yourselves to see as a praise of beauty, energy, skill (and wisdom),
b1 in my opinion virtue alone is the very best of all here. For: || In the N.-tune: ||
b2 beauty and a hero’s strength are to be regarded as the fruit of virtues; if one is born into a noble incarnation, if one becomes a rich Koṭīśvara [“Lord over 10 000 000”],
b3 a good reputation comes, virtues being the way to universal domination and the divine world.
b4 The coming together with the good ones [and] the reaching of the Nirvāṇa, virtue facilitates [this] without labour. 1. By virtue
b5 empowered the world-ruling king with [his] entourage walks to the airspace; the people on the four continents, as a fruit of virtue, submit to him.
b6 A person that has practiced virtue, does not come into misery, does not come into hardship. With the army of virtue all enemies</item>
